76561197997030136,Not Recommended,402020,33894936,Posted: 29 July,all,Alysandir,"TLDR:An atmospheric, psychological horror/supernatural-themed walking simulator that delivers a few cheap scares, but fails to deliver either a compelling story or satisfying exploration experience. Also personally found its themes offensive, YMMV. Can only recommend to fans of the genre and even then, wait for it to go on sale.Review:This your standard linear walking simulator/exploration game that takes place primarily in a creepy, broken-down amusement park. The gist of the narrative is that of a young mother searching for her child lost - who has presumptively been kidnapped by the evil spirits inhabiting the park - but within the first five minutes you'll realize that not all is as it seems, and that the protagonist is every bit as haunted as the park appears to be.About a quarter of the way through the game, maybe even less, you'll begin to understand that the story is not what you think it is and that the whole park experience (as well as that which follows it) isa visual representative of the protagonist's deteriorating mental state.What did I like about The Park?Visuals are fairly attractive - for decrepit amusement park, that is - although I will say that if you set the gamma as per the game's opening instructions, the game ends up being far too dark.Story pacing is decent, as you move quickly from area to area, keeping the game experience fairly fresh. The end area gets rather repetitive though, but I believe it's safe to say that's by design.This game does include a jog-mode to help you move more quickly, a feature I've come to appreciate in walking simulators.While the game does employ a couple jump scares - which I typically consider a cheap way to set atmosphere - the designers did include some downright creepy touches that you'll only notice if you're really paying attention.What I didn't like about The Park:It is very difficult to sympathize with the protagonist. You wouldn't think sympathizing with a mother searching for her lost child would be very hard, but within the first half hour I wager that you will begin to really not like this woman, and it steadily gets worse. I can't speak for everyone, obviously, but I find it very difficult to enjoy a game where I'm playing a character that I simply cannot empathize with, or put myself in their shoes.The length of the game is really quite short; even earning all achievements, I completed the game in under two hours, and to be frank, the actual exploration & discovery portion of the game occupied far, far less of that time. (The last area of the game really isn't about exploration and is more of a ""move through and experience it"" area.)I played two games from the beginning, and both times had some critical mouse input issues in both games that I had to alt-tab out to correct both times. Given how long this game has been out, that seems like a very weird bug to persist.The revealed narrative and the ending did not sit well with me at all, as I found it to be patently offensive and harmful towards a particular demographic in society. Spoilers ahead, so proceed at your own risk!As I mentioned before, the entire experience of The Park is an allegory for the protagonist's relapse into significant mental illness, and it's an extremely ham-handed one at that. We learn that the protagonist has had a rough life, with a possibly abusive father, a fiancee who dies in an accident not long after the conception of their child, a mother who doesn't want to know her, and in-laws that don't care a whit that she's the mother of their grandson. We also learned that she suffered from diagnosed postpartum depression. And for all of this, medical professionals treated her with both electroshock therapy (!) as well as a psychotropic drug (!) (based on the demonstrated effects), cheekily called 'Zolift.' (The actual drug, ""Zoloft,"" is *not* a psychotropic drug, BTW.)But it doesn't stop there; we are also treated to child-regression fantasies, anger displacement, escapist fantasies, and...oh yeah...the implied murder of her own child in order to, ""save him,"" from the same abusers that hurt her, when it's pretty clear that she's the abuser to him.At the risk of getting preachy, the premise of The Park is akin to taking every stigmatizing stereotype about mental illness and making it reality, with the end goal of...what exactly? There is no moral to this story; no point in the narrative where if she had just picked B instead A, everything might have turned out okay. It's clear from the narrative that the protagonist has no choice but to devolve into someone capable of murdering their child.If there's any judgment here at all, it would appear to be at the people who ""abandoned"" her or at the medical professionals who ""declared her cured"" and tossed her back into the real world with prescription medications as her only babysitter. The reality, however, is that no medical professional would send her away under medication without recurring therapy sessions any more than having tragedy in one's life leads to the kind of psychotic break on display here, so the whole thing comes off as very disingenuous.In short, this is the mental illness equivalent of a minstrel show, in that the representation of the causes, effects, and treatments of mental illness is given over to the worst stereotypes out there and offensive to those who battle it. The Park isn't a narrative done to be intentionally ""disturbing"" for reasons of entertainment; it's one that earnestly appears to believe that we're still living in the 1950s insofar as mental health treatment is concerned.You are certainly free to disagree with me, that this is just a story and that I shouldn't get all worked up over it. But even in 2017 there exists such a stigma against mental illness that people are afraid of seeking help for fear of being isolated or fired from their jobs (both of which happen in The Park), and for fear of being subjected to extreme therapies like electroshock or psychotropics (both of which happen in The Park), did we really need a game to reinforce that stigma?"
76561197969749884,Recommended,402020,32192665,Posted: 4 June,all,Sarkoth,"The Park is a quite short walking simulator with a mildly obvious story, average writing, yet extremely great art design and atmosphere. As part of a bundle or on sale 75% and more it's worth the two hours (tops) for a playthrough, but the standard asking price is quite too high."
,Recommended,402020,31942423,Posted: 24 May,all,niX,"Short story that will leave you with more questions than answers. If you like open-ended psychological games that really make you question what's going on, then this is for you.The story features a single mother named Lorraine who has lost her son in a theme park. She chases her son, and as time goes on, things take a drastic turn. It's about an hour long, all achievements can be obtained in one run.. making this a great ""I want to kill an hour or so"" type of game.ProsEasy to complete for completionists and for those who do not have a lot of free time to play games.Has some replayability, as some things make more sense the second time around. Lorraine will make a comment which will make more sense, or you will read a note you previously didn't understand which is now more easily understood.The events and story are open to interpretation which makes this a unique experience for each player. The story is what you as a player make of it. There are no right or wrong answers, as the conclusion is left very open ended.No enemies or puzzles, making this a simplistic and linear ""walking simulator"" type of game. This allows you to focus on the environments and what is going on around you with minimal stress.ConsSteep price for a game that will take an hour or MAYBE two hours if you replay it or take your time. This is probably best purchased on sale.The developers seem to boast about how ""thrilling"" this game is. I think their egos are a bit big in this aspect - as this game is hardly scary. There's a cheap few jump scares thrown in, but I don't consider to even count in ""horror"" games these days. This game is better described as being slightly disturbing. The highlight for me personally was the psyche of our main protagonist, but other than that any ""scary"" aspects are very shallow.The lead up is very slow. The game doesn't really get good until the last half hour.. at which point it's intense and in full swing. For an interactive game, there really isn't much to interact with. It takes over half of the game to get to the best parts, and then it's over.Font on some of the notes and letters in the game have small font that's hard to read (I play on an 18"" monitor), and there's no option to zoom in on anything. I cannot imagine somebody playing on a laptop or small screen being able to read anything in this game. Pretty big oversite, considering that most of what you interact with are letters/books/notes. The other annoying thing about collectibles is that you have to fidget around in order to interact with them properly. You practically have to be standing on top of an item or right in front of it before it can be reviewed.Giving this a recommend because I feel the overall experience outweighted the flaws, and I very genuinely enjoyed this."
,Recommended,402020,25006591,"Posted: 18 August, 2016",all,DeadlyDoRight,Well I did like the story behind it even if I didn't quite understand it thoroughly.Meant to be disturbing and not exactly something for children.Recommended for those who like creepy dark and disturbing tales.Not exactly survival horror but a rather haunting story about a mom looking for her sonand facing her own ambivalent feelings about herself as a mom and her mental issues.
,Recommended,402020,19152483,"Posted: 18 November, 2015",all,Bad Whippet,"What is it?""The Park"" is a very short narrative horror game (approx 2 hours' gameplay) set in a spookily derelict theme park.  You are seeking your son who ran ahead of you and has vanished out of sight.  As you search for him, you'll start to unravel the history of the park as well as begin to experience more of the horrors within both the park and yourself.  It's a game that probably merits the unfortunate tag ""walking simulator"" but in a positive way.  It doesn't feel laboured.  It plays equally well with gamepad and keyboard/mouse.  The story is dark and mysterious as it unfolds.Is it any good?It's VERY atmospheric.  If you like the idea of wandering around a small, desolate theme park in the dark, and to perhaps experience some of the rides as the story is narrated, this is a game you'll enjoy.  The horror elements are really well done, with a few small jump scares but no cheap tricks.  What was especially pleasant was to find my character had arms and legs, full reflection in mirrors and a shadow that occasionally made me jump when cast against a wall (bigger devs please take note - it was very nice not to be a disembodied head)!  The gamepad controls were very simple too.  A joy to play and, while sadly very short, a rich and dark experience as a psychological mystery unfolds, leaving you to ponder what on earth it all meant, and what your part in the story might have been.  The graphics, once inside the park, are tremendous, giving an EthanCarter-like vibe to the game.Anything not to like?I had a couple of glitches in trying to get it to run properly but a restart resolved it (my gamepad refused to be recognised at first).  The game is very short indeed, but I suspect it's meant merely to be a teaser game for Funcom's ""The Secret World"" (an MMORPG with free 7-day trial).  There isn't a concrete conclusion to the ending - which I imagine is deliberate, leading you to wonder who and what (can't say more because spoilers, but the story IS good).  There seemed to be a few loose ends where some things weren't explained, but again, that might have been artistic license rather than fault.Is it worth it?Personally, I think it's a wee bit short for the price, but the experience is worth it (if you played the equally excellent ""Homesick"" also on Steam, it's a similar sort of experience - different tale obviously).  On balance, I'm glad I bought it but the replay value (as with all games of this genre) is probably not that great.  I expect I will play it again at some point just like I'd watch a good movie again, but there won't be any variation in gameplay."
,Recommended,402020,18711887,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,thesawolf,"The Park is a superbly-crafted, gloomy, dark, atmospheric ""short story"" historically set inThe Secret World MMOuniverse (if you haven't checked it out, be sure to try it out, a 7 day free trial is included in the Extras menu of the game or you can get a 3-5 day trial key from a thread inThe Secret World discussion area). It's full of frights, general creepiness, intriguing lore and the frenetic search for a lost loved one all woven into an effectively told AND experienced dark tale.Graphics: 8/9- The graphics are well done overall. Nice details, shadows/lighting, especially in the world around you. In comparison to other games on the market, I'd have to say it's an 8. The character models feel/look odd at times.But in comparison to it's parent TSW, it's definitely a 9. It is awesome to see the ""historical"" versions/interpretations of a familiar sight in the TSW world.Sound: 8- The audio/bgm is appropriate, quietly brooding and dark. The voiceover work is well done and the voice actor cast for Lorraine was compelling and appropriately cast (the voice fits the game character).Gameplay: 7/8- It's simple and basic enough to make it non-obtrusive and keep the immersion intact. (which can be a double-edged sword) My only complaint isn't about the gameplay mechanics, or the length of the game, it's about the fact that I could not change my key or controller bindings. It's a subtle thing, but important for some folks that might have handicaps or are very preferential when it comes to keys (I'm VERY left-handed and prefer to use my numeric keypad for most things when using kb/m combinations). Also, it would've been nice to have a Zoom in/out feature for the lore items (notes, pamphlets, etc.) that you can pick up or interact with. Some of those fonts were just hard to read on my 52"" TV and my 27"" LED monitor.Story: 9- It was a well-told, immersively dark tale worthy of the TSW universe. I have no complaints. I thoroughly enjoyed the ride (figuratively and literally.. since there are some in the game. hehe)Value: 9- This is MY personal opinion. The amount of money paid for the amount/duration of entertainment I experienced made it worth it. Some people don't like the length of play time. Alot of those folks are A->B people, the kinds of people that don't stop to enjoy the world around them, to look through and embrace the lore presented. There's nothing wrong with it. I'm not one to judge. But neither should you. You are the ones that miss out, though, when you ""don't stop to smell the roses"". I enjoyed myself. It was worth the price tag. Like a good horror movie at the theatre.Overall Score: 8"
