,Not Recommended,402020,18850897,"Posted: 2 November, 2015",all,Katar,"WARNING: MINOR SPOILERSThis was a tough call, since I honestly enjoyed The Park.I wouldn't really describe this as a 'game', it's more like an 'experience' like an interactive haunted house as you guide Lorraine through The Park in the hopes of finding her son Callum. The game boasts on the cover (or steam page) as a ""Psychological horror experience"" dealing with ""with subject matter that might prove emotionally distressing to some. Player discretion is advised. “But that really isn't the case.  The Park tries to paint Lorraine as a down on her luck single mother dealing with drug and unresolved issues between her father and her son Callum but ultimately falls flat on its face. You simply have no incentive to care about Lorraine’s plight at all because she really has no story other than 'depressed single mom who might hate her kid'.The thing that I enjoyed about the park immensely was its atmosphere and sense of exploration. Wandering from one ride to the next and taking in the scenery and music of The Park. Funcom really nailed the entire 'creepy amusement park' aesthetic and it was a unique experience. The Park can be finished in about an hour and in about 2 if you take your time to see everything The Park has to offer. It's for this reason that The Park isn’t for everyone, and one of the reasons I'm giving it a negative review. There simply isn't the 'bang' there for your 'buck'.PROS-Atmospheric-Experience of 'The Park' - it's like an interactive haunted house if you let yourself get immersed in everything-Ambient sounds add to the atmosphere-Pacing - there are jumpscares, but they are few and far in-between and most of the 'scares' happen while riding the rides The Park has to offer rather than things popping out at you-Easy to get 100% achievementsCONS-Weak Story-Can be beaten in an hour-Not for everyone-13USD$ price tagCONCLUSIONPick up The Park during a sale."
