,Recommended,402020,29175683,Posted: 10 January,all,Andi,"I don’t like walking simulators.  They’re boring, they have nothing for you to do, no puzzles, no fights, and for the most part, nothing to find.  You just walk.  If I wanted to do that, I’ll go for a real walk.Before I purchased The Park, I had three other walking simulators… didn’t like any of them.  “So buy another one?”, you may ask.  Simple, I screwed up.  I thought there were some puzzles to solve.  “Why did you think that?” is the obvious follow up question.  Steam had their winter sale and I purchased several games and The Park was accidentally thrown into the mix, my own fault.  I had been reading several game summaries, (almost a dozen in all) and confused it with a different game which actually was a puzzle game.When I started The Park, I noticed that one of the tags was “walking simulator”.  CRAP.  I wanted to request a refund but something in the back of my mind said, “Just give it a chance.”  So I did… and I was pleasantly surprised.Pros:-Descent graphics.-A mystery unfolds as you play the game.-Creepy as hell.-All of the achievements are very easy to obtain.-When you enter the park, you can only go one way.  Eventually, you’ll come full circle and find that you’re at the entrance again.  If you look closely as you go down the path again, a couple of things are changed, adding to the creepiness.Cons:-Much to short.-A bit over priced because of how short the game is.The first walking simulator that I really enjoyed and it was over in 2 hours, and that’s me trying to explore every nook and cranny.All in all, I like this game.  I only wish it was longer."
,Recommended,402020,18743691,"Posted: 29 October, 2015",all,GracelessDeparture,"Tensely atmospheric, this is a well-told psychological horror story. About the same length as a feature film but more involving (and cheaper), I was gripped from the start. Make no mistake though, this is more story than game. Don't expect a test of skill and reactions, but do expect a test of your nerves.The main character Lorraine is believably flawed, with much of the exposition being delivered from her remembrances as you explore. It's hard not to be sympathetic as you discover more about her life as she talks. You're guided through your journey by a simple mechanic - right click the mouse and Lorraine will call out for her lost son, giving you audio and visual cues on where to go or what to examine next, with her calls becoming more frantic and scared as the story goes on. You're led to go on several of the titular theme park's attractions, each giving its own unsettling experience.The game comes bundled with a trial of The Secret World, the free to play MMO in the universe of which the story is set, and some costume items and high level gear to use in that game once you're there. You don't need to know The Secret World to enjoy the story, but those who have played will notice the references dotted throughout The Park.If you're looking for a chilling story that will leave your heart in your throat, then The Park is for you. If you're looking for something with more longevity and replay value, then this isn't going to satisfy. But for such a small price tag, this is a good buy for horror fans looking for a pretty unique if short experience."
76561198022820771,Not Recommended,402020,18824088,"Posted: 1 November, 2015",all,SocioPsycho,"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SRDEPdlKtb8The Park is officially designated as a first-person psychological horror adventure. Already I am at odds with the game, as adventure implies exploration, or a puzzle element, and horror implies the need for survival against something that is trying to kill you. The actual exploration in this game is limited to looking for your child, which is the whole point of the game, and there are no puzzles that you have to solve in order to continue. As to horror, the gameplay did nothing to add a feeling of doom, or threat to the character, out side of the story. There is no gameplay, no stealth, no challenge as to how to progress to the next zone, only the need to keep walking and get there. If anything, I would classify this game as a walking simulator with a spooky mentality.The strongest element is the story, with an immersive environment and a captivating, emotional lead character that draws you into the story. You are pulled into this dark, haunted, confusing theme park as you look for your child. One thing that takes away from the story is that you have to get on the various theme park rides; not because you think your child is on them, or because it is part of the story, but more because you feel you have to in order to collect some lore, and because the developers want you to experience the ride.The game is short (1-2 hours long) for price they are asking, I feel it needs more than just a really good story. I am conflicted about this game; the story was really good, but the gameplay was atrocious, with little interaction and no adventure element, or choice. For the story, I would recommend you watching a 'Let's Play' from a player you enjoy.Thanks for your viewership and support; for more videos click here:http:/www.youtube.com/user/SocioPyscho"
