76561198144842281,Recommended,402020,18737129,"Posted: 28 October, 2015",all,The Real Fallen,"This is exactly my type of game. I love these atmospheric short simulator games. The Park uses the Unreal Engine 4 so it not only looks great but runs great as well. When you first enter the park it is somewhat eerie, but peaceful and relaxing at the same time. As you get deeper into the park and further into the story it becomes more intense and eventually quite terrifying. Excessive jumpscares in games like these are not necessary to make the game scary, and this is exactly what I love about The Park. If your buying this game, however, dont expect any replay value as the story is only a little over an hour long. For $10 this game was worth it. Loved it."
76561197970568730,Recommended,402020,18955552,"Posted: 8 November, 2015",all,Gos,"The game starts off relatively nice and easy with broad day light and a mother going to ask for a lost teddy bear. Then her son runs off into The Park and Lorraine, the mother and protagonist, run after him.This is the point where the excrements hits the fan and you are all of the sudden in an old abandoned amusement park with a life of its own, but what a spectacular amusement park it is.I was expecting the game to be creepy and keep me on edge at all times. Funcom has attempted to achieve that by using jump scares and a rich athmosphere, both visually and audibly. And the increasingly creepy story they wish to tell in this game just adds to the tension. For my part, the experience was horror and my ticker reached max rate at some points in the game.However, I found that there were moments of sheer dullness in the game and although it picked up towards the end, they did not end on a ""horror""-climax which the game built up to. Instead they had a cinematic ending which was, more or less, lit up and was not notably exciting.The story element of this game, written by a team of award winning story tellers, is very much playing on strings of the Bonkers-guitar and they want to tell the tale of a very twisted woman. I feel the story line is good, albeit perhaps somewhat thin, but as you progress you get an insight of what's going on inside Lorraine head.The game play is fairly straight forward and the game rail roads you all the way through the game.You enter the park. You get on some rides. Along the the way you are narrated by Lorraines inner voice and you find clues, such as reports and notes, providing explanations and feeding you story. And finally you reach the final ""attraction"" which tries to tie it all together.There is no ""mini games"", puzzles, etc - just a story unfolding as you progress through the game.ConclusionI think anyone who cares more about the journey, rather than the destination, and who allows him- or herself to be scared and drawn into the game will enjoy The Park.So I would recommend it for those certain individuals.Watch my video review here:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=68QLPIwJ9xwWatch my Let's Play of The Park here:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ebC5ah1HwWY&list=PLKC1mMQjT7arfJyGAIC8f0ZD-uM6LNzgP&index=1Watch a compilation of me being scared in this game here:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VemHtG7yHYY"
