,Recommended,402020,18722921,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,Mr. Hugh Mannity,"At a first glance, The Park looks like your classic first person horror game that happens to take place in a creepy, abandoned and decrepit amusement park. But it crescendos much more than that.You play as Lorraine, a single mother who's lost her son, Callum, after visiting the Atlantic Island amusement park.Upon exiting the park just as closing time arrives, Callum tells her that he misplaced his teddy bear and storms into the amusement park to find it. With darkness quickly approaching and her son missing and ignoring her commands, Lorraine has to enter the park to find him, while strange things slowly begin to occur in the once friendly location.The story is a bit hit and miss, starting out weak but improving near the end of the game. As you explores the park at night and rides its various innocent yet menacing rides, the plot develops through Lorraine's monologue, which reveal her history and search for answers, and documents that are strewn about the park that reveal its dark past. Funcom have made no secret of the influence from games like Gone Home and The Vanishing of Ethan Carter, and the comparisons come almost instantly as you begin walking around the troubled theme park.It's also more involved than your average title, as you can ride the rides in the park (a Ferris wheel, rollercoaster, and the like), and look around at your surroundings while doing so. Controls are at a minimum with the ability to move and interact with any items, but I have to say I liked the inclusion of a run mechanic. It makes sense in this context – you’re in freaky hellscape of a park trying to find your son, after all – but it means that moving between sections doesn’t feel like a chore. The Park also uses call mechanic with the right mouse button that not only helps guide you to your next objective, but works brilliantly in the context of the game. Hearing Lorraine call out to Callum with increasing worry and panic is expertly done, as are the responses the player gets. It was these responses along with the swirling visual markers that ensured I knew where I was supposed to be going, although it wasn’t fool proof. There were a few moments where I had to wander around before I was able to get back on the right path, but I didn’t find it too frustrating or time-consuming, thankfully. There's also a decent amount of lore-building involved, and not just because of the Lovecraftian themes that are intertwined with the Funcom-verse. I actually enjoyed reading about various incidents at the park, and how they involve the cast although I did have an issue with some of the the scattered pages and documents you can find off the beaten path, detailing some of the game’s backstory. It seems unfortunate that some of them are nearly unreadable, as the font on these are tiny and blurry. A clearer font, zoom button or a subtitle option would have been an alternative, but as the game lacks it, unless you strain your eyes to read, you’ll be missing out on some of the backstory that ties it to Funcom’s other game, The Secret World.The strongest part however is the end of the game, which is both fantastic and unfortunate, as it’s such a strong and beautifully creepy finish that is way more terrifying compared to the rest of the experience. If only the game’s setting and story would have more like the last part of the game, it would have been a much more horrifying game.Overall, The Park is a well crafted narrative-driven adventure game, but there really is no reason to return once you’ve left The Park unless you want to get those missable achievements or analyse the letters and items again to figure out more of the backstory. However, if you want something a little different this Halloween, play this with the headphones on and the lights off."
,Recommended,402020,19188212,"Posted: 21 November, 2015",all,•SADBOY•,Really really great game. Its short but its completely worth it. You get to enjoy an amusement park (riding rides) while you have a rusty spooky scene. I've been wanting something like this for the longest time. The story is the cherry on top. I enjoyed everything about this. The atmosphere is fantastic. I only wish it was longer. 10/10 Highly recommend.
