76561198068072175,Recommended,402020,18732192,"Posted: 28 October, 2015",all,[ToC] Brother Goriel,"I dont write reviews but after playing this i just have the urge to say wow. Loved it from start to finish, didnt know what to expect as i had never played a walking simulater but the link to TSW was enough to pull me in. 5 stars and i would advise anyone looking for a good story and atmosphere to jump on board and buy it."
,Recommended,402020,18722018,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,Calebrated Gamer,"A shorter horror game (about 90 minutes) about an old haunted, abandoned amusement park, and the terrors that await within... How much of what you see is really there? Is it all in front of you, or just the workings of a guilty conscience of a young single mother slipping into madness? At the low price this game is offered, it's a steal to find out for yourself! It isn't the scariest of games, but the creepy atmosphere is nice, and the story really brings it all together!And be sure to check out my series on it if you get stuck, or want a funny outlook on this awesome game:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fVF5rQk4F1k&list=PL7Dj4-i15ObbnSAHyINoFTNqQj3Mc4bOS"
,Not Recommended,402020,18718073,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,Helping Hoof,"An entirely linear ""interactive"" story by Funcom which has some mild scare bits, a story that leaves you with a bad aftertaste in your mouth, and a whole lot of issues in terms of gameplay.- The XBox Controller's B button won't allow you to ""back"" out of menus. Nor does the ""back"" button.- The ""headthrobbing"" quickly gets on one's nerves.- The player character narrates the story from time to time - turning off running while she talks. This is really obnoxious since the game is essentially a walking simulator. You advance the story by going from one park ride to another and there's a lot of ground to cover in between them.- Talking about running; you can't run until you get to the point where the game tells you what key to use to run. Forget trying it before that point as that particular key is not ""active"" until that point.- Interaction hovertext is glitchy and may appear in random positions and half out of the screen while you pass by an item, or appear in the center of the screen when you're nowhere near the item.- Especially in the rollercoaster part of the level there are some longer texts which only flash by and are impossible to read as a result. Even when playing the game twice.- The game is so linear it could have been ""on rails"" if not for the part where you're searching for badly hidden interactive objects along the road. They even go so far as to put you in the middle of a round area, and then put the bogeyman on the road so you can only go around it in one direction.- On lower resolutions, the scraps of paper you find are impossible to read. On a laptop with a resolution of 1366x768 I could not read the letters on the papers I found even with my nose pressed against the screen! Really a big oversight.- Areas shut off from being revisited once you exit them, the game literally demanding the player to push forward to the next area, up until you've found everything you need for the story to progress to the House of Horrors, when all of the park is suddenly open and accessible for no apparent reason.- The in-game lore is a little ""out there"" for people who have not played The Secret World and understand the players at work there. There's barely any information for people to piece that story together properly, except for a lot of mentioning of places found on Solomon Island, something the player would have no attachment to one way or another if they have not played The Secret World.- Apparently the spoken ""Don't let them take me"" is supposed to be ""Don't take me"" according to the subtitles.- I guessed at ""the big reveal"" about ten minutes into the game and only had it confirmed in the last FMV of the game.- Did I mention the game is really short? We're talking less than 2 hours playtime here.I'm happy to obtain the special items for my TSW account, so I at least have something for my troubles, but there's no replay value here besides trying to complete the achievement list if you missed anything on your first go.I really wish Funcom had put some more effort into making the game more engaging. This could have been so much better, considering the park's background story. Instead they put the focus on something entirely unrelated and used the park as a backdrop. Such a shame.Lastly, just so I'm not a complete negative Nancy; there were a few good things about the game;+ The atmosphere is great. It's what was to be expected; dark places, wind howling, the occasional sound that makes you wonder if you really heard it.+ The chipmunk is sufficiently creepy and pops up in places you least expect him to be in. He's not overused, but the amount of his appearances are just right for the length of the game.+ The rides are decently thought out even if it's clear they're separate instances. It's not as seamless as I would have liked, but it's barely a bother considering the limited amount of games which have good carnival rides in them.+ The role of the bogeyman when it concerns the rides was a nice touch.+ The house of horrors had just the right amount of creep to it, although I had expected some more events when interacting with things like the faucet or some of the doors.+ For players of The Secret World, there was a nice amount of additional lore to gather.Still; I do not recommend this game in this state. This was not the right place to have a story about post-natal depression. It would have been better served following the trail of death from the park's opening to its inevitable closing, and go in deeper on the cause for the supernatural events that took place there."
