,Recommended,402020,18731499,"Posted: 28 October, 2015",all,Minnesota Menace,"Let be break this down for you as simple as possible.What FunCom has done here is create something that many TSW players were looking for in game when visiting the amusement park while questing.  They had created this visually fantastic area filled with mystery and intrigue.  All I could think about when running that series of quests is that I wanted a better, more in depth look at the park, and this game delivers the content I was looking for.If you have not played through the story in The Secret World, much of this game will seem linear and boring.  It expands on what we learn and gives us another taste of the darkness that stood out in my first playthrough.  As TSW is broken up into sections and areas, you have to leave that section to further advance your character.  Having a short reprise, for me at least, was a nice throwback.  If they make more games like this, based on the other sections of the game, I will probably buy them as well.I honestly think this is a good start in a new direction for FunCom, and that more of these games, with larger and further developed storylines will be worth the playtime.I feel like they made this game for me.  Thank you FunCom."
76561198044337564,Recommended,402020,18720469,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,Progmagnan,"Note: This review is after my first play through of the gameI originally saw trailers for The Park months before it came out and once it became available to pre-order on Steam, I bought it; there was the advantage that it was also on sale but this was my first ever pre-order on Steam and I am happy to say, I was not in any way disappointed.To be clear, the game tells you it is a narrative driven game, much like games from Tell Tale or the game Gone Home, this means actions are limited in place of following/taking part in the story. So to those who expect anything else, you only have yourself to blame.I really enjoyed this game, the atmosphere is immersive as it blends a perfect mix of visuals and audio to keep you tense and constantly pressing the right mouse button. The game itself is short but that is not neccessarily a terrible thing, games do not need to be long they only need to be entertaining and padding them out with repetitive game play often only takes away from the experience.If you are new to horror, this may not be a bad choice, the game is very easy to get into and easier to get lost in.Edit: I am seeing a lot of reviews complaining about the game being a narrative driven game. I am not sure why because the game, the trailer, the developers all said it is a narrative driven game. People had the same complaints about Gone Home and the Vanishing of Ethan Carter but you never hear people complain about about any other game like this ""It didn't say it was twin-stick shooter"" or ""it didn't say it was a third person shooter"", so why should a game have to apologize for what it is?If you don't like narrative driven games, don't buy them."
