,Not Recommended,402020,29949617,Posted: 15 February,all,RoninOtter,"The short of it:The Park is replete with ""horror game"" clichés.  Cheap jumpscares, a creepy setting, flashbacks, disturbing imagery, and a flair for messing with reality all make their appearances.  There's also no compelling characters, combat, choices, gameplay, dialogue interaction, or payoff.  The obtusely-simplistic story is entirely unable to stand on its own, and has an ending that's so dull and predictable that my friends and I called it within the first 5 minutes.  The only thing about the game that's scary is it implies that Zoloft turns you into a pyschopath...The long of it:Set within the universe of""The Secret World"", ""The Park"" is meant to be a spin-off game.  Now, a spin-off needs something to stand on its own, such as expanding upon a small element of a larger story arc that ends up having its own dramatis personae.  Otherwise, it's not a spin-off, but rather just an episode of a long-arc TV show where if you haven't seen everything leading up to it makes absolutely no sense.  Playing ""The Park"" as an outsider of the MMORPG is like being the one person in the room with a bunch of die-hardGame of Thronesfans that has never seen a single epsiode or read any of the books.  You tilt your head at the screen and ask ""So, what the ♥♥♥♥ is going on?""  While it might speak to those who play the MMORPG, it's an atrocious ambassador to that larger world for the rest of us, because if ""The Secret World"" is anything like ""The Park"" in terms of story or gameplay, you couldn'tpayme to play it.While walking through the eponymous setting, your point of view is as the narrator and candidate for ""worst mother on the planet.""  Note that I don't say you ""play"" this character.  This is because you're merely looking through her eyes as you walk around the environment and things happen.  The entire thing is effectively (and often literally) on rails, and you have no ability to affect the story based on your actions.  There's no way to ""win"" or ""lose,"" nor can you have any impact on the events unfolding whatsoever.  Sure, some of the imagery can be demented and weird, but it falls flat at being scary since nothing ever threatens you as the player and there are no tasks to be punished for failing.  You have literally nothing to do except visit various different places, and sit down to ride something while listening to faceless voices talk.The only other ""character"" you encounter looks so visually out-of-place that his appearance is far more comical than disturbing, and he never grabs your attention long enough for you to want to know anything else about him.  The mystery of whether he's a hallucination, demon, or other such entity isn't compelling at all since he has absolutely no effect upon the main character in the end.  Just like the protagonist's aggravatingly disobedient child, he's flat and forgettable.  (There's another character you see at the end, but he's so forgettable that I actuallyforgot to mention him in the review, and had to place this note here after the fact.)But here's the absolute worst thing of all for me about ""The Park"":  Its astoundly ignorant and offensive treatment of depression and mental health.  Any and all remaining respect for the game I might otherwise have had is vaporized by the inflammatory and damaging portrayal of the effects of real-world medications that the game presents.I'm happy to see that I'm not alone in this observation.Perhaps there is some alternate supernatural explanation which one would need to have played ""The Secret World"" in order to know about, but based purely upon the context of what ""The Park"" tells us, the possible side-effects of being medicated for depression include hallucinations and murdering your children.  It relegates depression to the realm of ""insanity"" where mild seratonin imbalance medications (they riff on Zoloft with ""Zolift"") are the colloquial ""crazy pills.""As someone who is close to multiple people who medicate against depression and who has suffered from depression himself, this is unforgiveable, and drops ""The Park"" to the absolute bottom of my list of games to recommend to anyone.  If I could, I'd rank it below ""Dead Mountaineer's Hotel."""
,Not Recommended,402020,29835413,Posted: 10 February,all,JazzTune,"It's short, but what it lacks in length it makes up in quality.Just kidding, it kind of blows. Someone bought it for me and I still felt ripped off."
76561197993856374,Recommended,402020,18726454,"Posted: 28 October, 2015",all,Rictus,"If, like me, you like the basic genre of ""walking simulators"" and if, like me, you're a player of The Secret World, this is a perfect companion piece to the story of Solomon Island and of course Atlantic Island Park in contemporary times.I've finished the game in about two hours which seems to be standard length for this genre (IIRC I finished Gone Home in a similar time), but might be on the longer side, since I really do try to explore if a game styles itself exploratory. The Park is rather linear in that regard, so there is little exploring of hidden places, but plenty of exploring of scenes, especially in the later parts.There are a lot, and I mean a lot, of allusions to The Secret World, most of which are not pertienent to the story here, but a nice little touch for Secret Warriors. Beware, if you haven't finished New England in TSW there may be slight spoilers here, depending on how much you pick up and can draw the right conclusions.The atmosphere can be nothing short of terrifying if you're able to immerse yourself. There is some excellent sound design helping this and some of the scenery and set pieces are sufficiently creepy, even if the're not really innovative. The old standbys (creepy dolls, flocks of birds, etc.) work for a reason.I don't want to go into story, since in my opinion it's mostly a matter of personal taste if you like a story or not, but let it be said, as mentioned before, that it fits very well within the universe of The Secret World, not only because of atmosphere and ""shout outs"", but also because of theme.In the end, I recommend The Park with the caveats mentioned in my review. For me personally it was fully worth the 10 € I paid."
,Recommended,402020,18720195,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,Artificial Unintelligence,"Horror games have a special place in the pit of all consuming darkness that is my heart, and psychological horror games have an even more special place. Now, let's break this down.The game follows a depressed mother looking for her lost child in a really creepy amusement park named Atlantic something. Moving on, the game soon takes a turn for the worst when the sky darkens and you wander around with this woman talking to you, telling the most tragic (but very well written) story about her life, her contradicting views on Callum, her son, and some conversation between her and a skinny, well dressed Oogie Boogie from The Nightmare Before Christmas (if you don't know what I'm talking about please re-evaluate your entire life). The game seems to follow the story of Hansel and Gretel (follow the path and when you see the swan boat ride, ride it to get an achievement and a man retelling the story). References to the tale are mentioned here and there.If you've played Outlast before (which I reccomend HIGHLY if you haven't), then you know what jumpscare and gore horror is. This is not that. I'm not saying there's not blood and bodies in this game, but the numbers, compared to Outlast, are few; however, this game is scary, but more psychologically.Pros:-fantastic story-creepy atmosphere-sp00ky soundtrackCons:The only con I have about this game is that it's really short. You can finish it within an hour, which sucked because I really got into the story.8.5/10Hasta la vista, baby-Citrus"
