,Recommended,402020,26421184,"Posted: 4 November, 2016",all,LeoQueen082,"I say recommended under the circumstances that you buy it on sale. And that you also keep this in mind: it takes place in another universe. This exists in the universe of another MMORPG game this company has made. Some of the notes and the things you read/see have to do with that game and are just affecting the universe of this game, but doesn't add or take away anything from the plot.ALSO. Major ::Trigger Warnings:: in this game as well!talks of postpartum (wow, that's one word? thanks google) depression/psychosis, suicide attempts, and there's a part in the game where it shows the character used to cut herselfI would say prepare yourself to be triggered, but it's spaced sporadically throughout the game and shouldn't affect your ability to enjoy the game.So if you don't keep the idea that the game resides in an already-existing universe in mind, this game can and will get confusing really fast. If you've never heard of or know the symptoms of the mental illness Lorraine has, it can also get confusing.Overall, it's a good game though! There's a lot of times where the story isn't clear-cut and that is what makes you want to continue on to figure out what's going on. The voice acting can be questionable at times, especially with the ""Callum"" Shout mechanic. Sometimes the shout doesn't match the monologues that she goes through and it can be comical at best, pulling you from the experience.Other than that, and the ending having more to do with the universe their other game created, the game is a pretty spoopy game. It got me a few times (but then again I'm also a huge loser when it comes to scary games)."
76561198067100243,Recommended,402020,20625473,"Posted: 19 January, 2016",all,Wyrmblez,"Been playing games on Steam for a while, but never took the time to write a review. I felt obligated to do this one because this game is a mixed bag for some, but I think it is an engaging interactive story, and that´s very much what this ¨game¨is. A spinoff from the MMO, The Secret World, you enter an amusement park, a setting from the original game to explore the sinister stories and tragedies that still haunt this decrepit theme park. You walk along and follow the rides and the narrative, and try to find and read the scattered letters and notices, and listen to Lorraine´s monologues about life. I call this an ïnteractive¨story because you can´t really lose, and even with my terrible sense of game direction, you can´t really get lost. While this game´s story was not a thriller, with some awesome twist at the end, I found it to be a tour de force that made me interested in finding where the story was going. The main character was enjoyable as a flawed and very human person, and I feel a lot of attention to detail was paid to making Lorraine seem like a real person with real problems, caught up in unreal circumstances. The ending of the game is a bit of a puzzler, but again, so interesting that I continued trying to research the game after it was finished, and even briefly piqued my interest in checking out The Secret World (but who has time for MMOs with almost 200 games in the library). While reading, I came across this quote from the creator that I wanted to share:""Everybody's had that dream where they fall,"" Bylos says. ""Most people have had that nightmare where they wake up because they fell from a height -- I want that feeling from people, especially as you go through the House of Horrors, the sense that the bottom is rushing up and you just can't stop it. It's inevitable.""  --Joel BylosIt was because of this quote that I came here to recommend this game, because it did exactly what the creator wanted to do, and I consider that to be a success. As the ending drew near, I couldn´t stop myself, and I did feel that rush of an impending end that made me both anxious and excited. While the game´s ending felt like a well-what-do-you-think-happened, I was glad for the experience. While some might want to wait for this to be on sale, as the game is maybe 1-2 hours at most, I encourage games to be the new medium for storytelling, and The Park is not to be missed for those who enjoy eerie atmospheres, realistic characters, and dark stories."
