76561198046892059,Not Recommended,402020,23147504,"Posted: 22 May, 2016",all,Aurom K,"Much as I would like to give this game a positive review, I simply find that I can't in good conscience.  The fact of the matter is that it did not scare me.  I won't lie and say that I am the world's fore-most authority on horror games, but I have played a few of them, and The Park is probably the least effective of the lot.  This may well stem from the fact that it is a walking simulator.  Now perhaps I should have realized this before I bought it, but I think the very fact that I did not, even after watching the video ad and reading the steam store text, is rather telling.Unfortunately the story, which is very clearly the main focus of the game, is nothing terribly special.  It centers around a young (maybe, it's sort of hard to tell) mother, her child, and the amusement park which (rather indirectly) caused their lives to go to hell.  What's frustrating about it is that the bones of the narrative are pretty solid, it simply wasn't expanded enough.  It's clear almost from the get-go that the owner of the themepark was doing something not terribly nice, but they really never reveal what his intention was, or even what precisely it was that he was doing.  They bring up an incident from the past in which the park's mascot murdered at least one teenager (maybe more, it isn't very specific) but then his part of the narrative is never expanded on.Speaking of the ice-pick wielding chipmunk mascot, there's a bit of a running theme with him showing up and attempting to scare the hell out of the player, but the fact is that this tactic simply doesn't work in a situation where one knows for a fact that he's not going to hurt the main character.  I suppose you could argue that I didn't properly ""lose myself in the medium"" or some such, but personally it seems like that's more the ""game"" failing to draw me in than me being unwilling to suspend my disbelief.  It's sort of like reading a book where, half way in, an extremely contrived situation shows up and threatens to kill off the protagonist.  No one will fall for it, because you're only halfway into the book, and it's exceptionally clear that the author isn't going to switch viewpoints after so much work developing their main character, so what is supposed to be a tense situation just feels like something you have to slog through in order to continue the story.But I digress.  Probably the best feature of The Park is its atmosphere, and the quality of its visual design.  Easily the creepiest moments came not when I was paying attention to the story itself, reading notes or listening to the protagonist's internal monologue, but when I spent the time to inspect some well designed and indelibly disturbing thing that happened to be sitting around in the environment.  I remember one moment particularly well when I had to walk past a bizarre bird-like sculpture that was set along one of the paths in the park.  Not only was the character design interesting and unique in its eeriness, the game devs had textured in what I could swear were bullet holes in the thing, which made me almost certain it was going to spring to life the moment I turned my back, and start following me.  More's the pity when it didn't.I suppose that's really the whole theme of why I can't recommend this as a game; more's the pity when it didn't.  There was a lot of potential for greatness here, but virtually all of it went unfulfilled.  I wouldn't say that there were no good moments in the game, otherwise it wouldn't have that tantalizing potential, it's more a matter of there not being enough.  All in all it's about like going through a haunted house, except you don't have any friends with you to make it more enjoyable, and there's only a couple of actors who are more or less content to just stand there and assume their costume is creepy enough."
