76561198078673632,Recommended,402020,18740173,"Posted: 29 October, 2015",all,Melyc'inya,"Amazing, A+, fingers crossed Funcom continues to make this sort of thing until they run out of ideas. Which is hopefully never.I would say the Park is like an interactive movie--playtime is about the length of one, you can't die, and there's no quicktime or combat. You explore a horrifying amusement park while trying to find your child, and witness everything fall apart in something more immersive than a movie would be. If you prefer challenging content this probably won't be your cup of tea, but if you like a terrifying atmosphere and a dark horror story, I highly recommend checking it out.This game deals with depression (and how terribly it was handled in the 80s), and a pretty dark side of parenthood. There are also a few bright flashes on the rollercoaster, though nowhere near as bad as the trailer--they seemed pretty well spaced out, as I recall. Do exercise caution if any of these might be harmful or upsetting.The Park is tied in with the MMO The Secret World--it takes place in a location that exists in TSW and drops a few names, but in no way does it require having played TSW first. It's perfectly self-contained, and you won't lose any of the horror if you only play the Park. However, I do recommend at least taking advantage of the one-week trial this game gives you, because TSW has similarly strong story and atmosphere and the majority can be played solo if you so choose. It'll also give you reason to re-play the Park after you finish Solomon Island, to see what extra context you recognize.All in all, the Park is high on atmosphere, with a few jump scares and a lot of psychological horror that gets steadily heavier as you near the end.Q̖̣͖͔͍̭u͎̮͖̼̗̝͍͢a͟c̭̪̘k҉̖ ̠͈̤̲q̣̣̜̺̝͟ṷ̸̙̯̣ḁ̳̣͘ͅc͙͈k̲͔̺̖̲ ̸̘͚̟͖̰̹q̙͎͉̤̳̯ͅu̬̭̥ac̳̟͟k͕̪͔ ̹̬͕̭͖q̞͙̖̬̬u̪̗̬͙a͉̖̙͖͈̥͙c̫͚̭͍͢ḱ̦.̦"
