76561198083068272,Recommended,402020,22670017,"Posted: 27 April, 2016",all,TheBeak,"Gory thrillseekers, jumpscare lunatics and those looking for mile a minute onslaughts of ghots and zombies probably won't get much out of The Park.  Much in the vein of Sylvio, The Park offers a bleak, desperate slow burn where you slowly explore your surroundings and deal with the mysteries at hand.  There's even less combat than Sylvio and despite The Park's slant towards a nail-gnawing walking simulator the game's formula works and have a way of digging its way under your skin thanks to some frightening flashback sequences, the main character's emotional breakdown and the fact that the deeper you go into the game the more helpless you feel.The premise is simple.  Mother Lorraine and her son Callum are about to head for home after a long day at the park but Callum left his teddy bear inside.  Despite Lorraine's rocky emotional past with her son she agrees to be the hero and find the boy's missing bear.  Within instants of being let back in the park to begin your search, it's obvious that evil forces trap you inside and soon Lorraine is on a journey filled with taunting phantoms, malfunctional amusement park rides, narrow escapes, suspenseful chases and all sorts of danger.  The game plays out like a point n' click adventure with the player tasked with tracking down the son by exploring all of the park's lucid areas, reading notes that reveal the park's history as well as the darkness in Lorraine's past.  Though you can't die and none of the puzzles are extremely difficult, you'll find the grim atmosphere begins suffocating the senses like a blanket of despair.  The establishment's supernatural denizens will play constant tricks on you, proving that your presence is unwanted.This game's got great atmosphere with rich graphics creating breathtaking environments, rich backgrounds, lush use of light and shadow and a design aesthetic that gives even The Park's rickety, rustic rides each a personality of their own.  Not only do the graphics create a noticeable feel of decay and isolation but the sound delivers as well with haunting drones, the sudden rumble of ressurected machinery, appropriately evil dialogue from the demons and Lorraine's mental/verbal battle with herself where she reveals some particularly disturbing revelations about motherhood.  This is the purest definition of a psychological horror game as it borrows influences from film including the works of David Lynch, Jacob's Ladder, The Machinist, Session 9, Tourist Trap, Funhouse and perhaps John Carpenter.  The experience really comes together in the dark on a good set of headphones.As for gameplay, things aren't too deep and there's not alot of actions to perform but they all make sense in the context of this cinematic gaming experience.  You can run, walk, collect/read documents, pick up an item or two, use a flashlight, ride the park's rides and interact with switches/levers and do whatever it takes to progress.  Sometimes time will violently warp between past, present and sheer madness, maintaining an aura of a creeping unknown dogging you until the game's very end.  The story held me in for the long haul and a late game sequence inside of a funhouse gets increasingly hopeless as it progresses.Though Steam can certainly cough up a few titles disguised as horror that end up being nothing more than incomplete garbage, The Park managed to captivate my attention from the beginning until the very end.  It took me roughly 4 hours to beat the game with all achievements and searching high and low for every single note to read and piece of the story.  Depending on how thorough you are it could take as little as 2 hrs to finish the game in a single sitting.  If anything, the game could have been longer because it really does grab you once you get into it but I got it on discount and was very pleased with my purchase.Pros:-Entrancing story well told through notes, collectibles, flashbacks and character monologue/dialogue.-Excellent setting makes for intense feelings of isolation.-Well-designed areas and nicely detailed graphics.-Hair-rising sound design.-Unfolds like an interactive movie with cool ride sequences.-Some truly spooky sequences and set pieces.-Fairly open set-up letting you progress somewhat how you want.Cons:-Pretty short even if you're an achievement hunter.-Not alot of challenge.-Minimal puzzle solving.-Really only incentives to play through once (unless you really liked the story, which I didOverall:  8/10Despite the short length and some of The Park's flaws, the story was engrossing and the game was hard to put down once I got started.  It's not a typical horror game and wants to deliver a few righteous blows to the player's psyche before all I said and done.  This probably isn't an adventure for everybody but those that enjoy a twisty plot, pitch black atmosphere and a sense of mystery with their adventuring should really enjoy Funcom's admirable efforts!"
