,Recommended,402020,18718222,"Posted: 27 October, 2015",all,MelficeOne,"Man, is it just me or has it gotten P.T. in here? But I am skipping ahead.The Park is a Game by Funcom, the minds behind The Secret World and it plays in the Amusement Park from the same game. If you are solid in TSW Lore, skip this next paragraph if not this might helpAn old man decided to harness the magic power of Solomon Island, he did so by constructing a park and using it as a Magic Circuit. However, Usually those kinds of things never go well, and it so happens that the Magic very much tainted the Park. And so during construction and while the park was running terrible accidents and way too much death happened - Until the Player Character comes along and finishes/fixes what the old man once started.This game happens before that happens.The Park is one of those experiences you want to be over and you want that to be soon. In a good way. The game can be finished in about 2 hours and leads you through something I never really considered to be scars - a deserted Amusement Park at Night. (Given we are in ♥♥♥♥ed Up Land, but yes.)The Game opens with a message telling you that it ""might play around with control and Audio settings"" - just to f**k with you and yes, controls feel a bit sluggish at times, especially towards the end.the Story is conveyed through the Main character, a mother whose son ran off into the Park to look for his lost teddy bear, talking to herself and occasionally when you Press X To Jason. You will also find reports, Letters and newspaper clippings, but thats not the norm here.the Atmosphere is just creepy. the park is very small but still manages to creep the living♥♥♥♥♥♥out of me at times. when you step into the rides you'll find that the game does not play with the usual Horror Game Frights, but more relateable ones. Losing your kid in a Park, going 60+ on a Ferris Wheel. The fact that you can only look around on those... Really gives you an increased feeling of helplessnessAudio - there is almost no music, save for a few notes around some rides and soundwise I didnt pick much up either, However onething providing mild discomfort was that at times whey would play a Bassy sound.Overall the game is (very) short for its price, but an Experience to be had. It also extends on one of the major points in the first area of TSW.Honestly tho, this game left me with a lot more Questions than answers. Mostly because the end just churned my brain with very cryptic stuff"
