,Not Recommended,402020,20720355,"Posted: 24 January, 2016",all,One Step Ahead Delcat,"I really wanted to like this game.  It came so close.  But at the end, it's tepid at best, and it definitely left me with a bad taste in my mouth.I enjoy experience games and walking simulators, and I enjoy short games.  The play time felt just right to me, and there weren't any bugs or lag.  I liked the atmosphere, I liked the idea, I liked the environments.  There are some solid moments in here, including one of the best-executed scares I've seen in a while--theswan headmoment is perfection in subtlety, unreality, and understated terror.Unfortunately, that happens within the first twenty minutes of the game, and it's all downhill from there.From the beginning of the game I was already going""Sorry about your definitely dead son that you very definitely killed by the way you're in a mental institution none of this is really happening"".  Seriously, from the opening lines.  It's not at all subtle.  With obvious dark magic tomfoolery gadding about, I was hoping that one of the other plotlines alluded to would go somewhere, but they devolved into cliches.  Actually, the entire game devolved into cliches.  The first few scares are inexplicable and intriguing, but they have explanations slapped onto them fast and hard.  WHAT'S BEHIND THE MYSTERIOUS MASCOT?Some college kid who was driven to yawn-worthy slaughter by eldritch abominations.WHAT WAS THAT THING GLIMPSED FROM THE OCTOTRON?Literally the Babadook, also eldritch abominations.WHAT IS THE SECRET OF THE PARK?Blahblahblah eldritch abominations, you get to a point where you look away in secondhand embarrassment every time they ""cleverly"" put in a glaring Lovecraft reference, culminating in the maximum cringe of WARRIOR CTHULHU t-shirt on the damned dead kid at the end.By the end of the game, there are literally bleeding walls, ""scary"" children's drawings, ""eerie"" nursery songs, dismembered baby dolls, the ""throw a dart at the Horror section of Netflix"" works.  Nothing we haven't seen before a zillion times,unless you count the so very dead kid drawing and labeling a carrot on an otherwise unrelated message JUST SO THEY COULD GET ""ROT"" OUT OF IT.That is admittedly some new levels of ham-fisted.If it had been just cliches, I could have left the game a little disappointed but remembering it fondly.  But the obvious reveal of the primary antagonist to bethe mother herselfmade me distinctly uncomfortable for a number of reasons.  Spoilers abound, so:Look, I'm not saying there's no such thing as bad mothers, or abusive mothers.  Far from it.  I think another game (the title of which I will not reveal as it's a spoiler for it) handled the idea quite well, making the mother the antagonist but a character you could understand and sympathize with while still disliking.  Lorraine, on the other hand, is a mess of a character.  Are we supposed to sympathize with her, hate her, what?  The game offers a little room for us to sympathize, but then seems to demand it back, leaving us in the uncomfortable position of being expected to hate a single mother on welfare battling serious depression.  Seriously, that is what we're intended to vilify here.  Someone in an absolutely awful situation doing the best she can.  Because...oh no!  She takes PRESCRIPTION MEDICATION!  For a condition that we see point-blank causes her to have terrible psychotic episodes!  What a terrible mother you are, Lorraine.And then it's also eldritch abominations or something.  Of course.  Game, do you even KNOW what you want?  Other than people to buy The Secret World?So, yeah.  Gameplay?  Fine.  Length?  Fine.  Atmosphere?  Awesome.  Idea?  Great.  Execution?  Pretty nice.  Predictable plot falling apart into so many unused threads you could make spaghetti out of them with eye-rolling cliches as the sauce?  Dealbreaker.Give this one a pass, you have other places to lay out your cash."
