,Recommended,402020,18848996,"Posted: 2 November, 2015",all,DMStewart,"Very cool. Well done. Many games claim to be ""atmospheric"" and only a few truly achieve the claim. Most of the creepiness of the game comes from your own mind. Its what you dont see that is always more creepy than what you do see. Perfect example, at one point in the path through the park a shadow from a fern looks like a hand. Just as youre walking by it moves in the breeze bringing it in front of the light, making it look like a hand just reaches out a little from the dark into the light.Now, Im sure that happens a lot in these types of games. But without properly setting the atmosphere, no one is in the right state of mind to even notice or care. I wont get into any of the story either. Firstly because I only fired it up fast to see how it looked, ran, etc. (Of course I stayed 40 mins into it). Secondly, what I know about the story so far is only enough to spark my own curiousity...and set it down the path to the creepy and unknown. Better yet, a story line that I dont want to know but one that I am inadvertanly going to have to live through.The writers and designers really did a great job in coming together. As someone who has spent half my career writing everything from basic hard news to a vast array of fiction, the medium of video games has been a place where the finished product is either great, or terrible. Or worse yet, it's totally mediocre and goes by unnoticed. But this very eaily couldve bee ruined with the slightest miscalculation. The cutting of one corner couldve damned this into mediocrity. I hope everyone who contributed to this project gives themselves credit for getting everything just right.Price: $10 or less is really where this needs to be. I just picked it up in the final minutes of the sale. Since the product description says its about a 1-2 hour game I instantly compare that to the price of a movie. Dont get me wrong, in Unreal4 it looks like it should be $29.99. Had they been less transparent theyve couldve charged $30 and received all negative reviews. So I believe they also know the true value and respect the players' wallets.So its all good all the way around. I would complain of no Crossfire support but it runs smooth for me on a single card at 70-80 fps on a single 290x Lightning. (If you have any other 290x expect to get about 50-65 fps maxed out settings)-DMS"
,Recommended,402020,35137369,Posted: 22 September,all,Ｇａｌａｃｔｉｃ　Ｇｒａｓｓ,"The Park: Game ReviewA bland psychological taleWhere do I start this review? During my time withThe ParkI realized how a game creator can turn a simple tale such asHanzel & Greteland twist it to apill addicted mother killing her innocent son.The game opens with you, the mother, driving up to this theme park, Atlantic Oak or something along those lines. Your son Callum is in the car while yoiu get out and just walk away. Apparently we left hisTeddy Bearinside the park and we must retrieve it. You walk extremely slow during this section and are unable to look at anything. You can either beeline straight to the ticket booth where the game progresses or you can walk yourself up this curvy hill into some mist? I'm not sure why they added that other than a cheap [spiler] achievment. [/spoiler] This guy is inside the ticket booth and he gives us the clear to go into the theme park to look for thisTeddy Bear.During the ""First Chapter"" we are allowed to Sprint, Call for our son Callum, and examine clues that give us more information on the theme park. While calling for Callum a blur will appear on your screen indicating you to go whatever dirction and Callum will call out with a ""THIS WAY MOMMY!"" Which adds some creepiness to the story. The atmosphere of the Park is actually pretty chilling. I did play with the brightness up slightly higher than suggested which may have affected some of the more ominous and scary portions of the first chapter. At this point, Callum has us running to the Swan Ride, on the way there we learn that the Mascot forThe Park""Steve/Chad the Squirrel"" is not liked very much and people think the person is a creep. After going down this small hill ight inside of the park, we are greeted by Callum and watch him joyously jump onto a swan boat and take the dark ride into the tunnel. We then get on the next boat and venture into the cavern, where we are greeted with ""Hanzel and Gretel"" projected onto the cave walls. The story goes through how their parents hated them, to the point they were going to leave them in the forest to die. Hanzel is like ""I'll go out and make a trail of rocks and breadcrumbs to the house!"" But we all know it doesn't work and birds eat that♥♥♥♥♥♥right up. Anyways, they find a house made of candy after being dropped off in the forest and let to die for three days. Hanzel, being the little tubby he is, ate the walls of the candy house. An older woman then comes out and offers them food. Little did they know she wanted to eat poor little tubby. Gretel being the smart gal she is, asks the witch how to clean the oven properly and then rightfully pushes her in. Then the kids eat the witch and are so filled and happy. During this story the boat is knocked around a couple of times and the Mascot, Chad, is seen inside watching us for a breif moment.Chapter 2After this boat ride, we are allowed to venture over to the Ferris Wheel. The Ferris wheel portion of the game provides us with all the info we need to start to feel horrible for our character. We learn her husband died while she was pregnant with Callum. We also learn that all we wanted for Callum was to have a great life, but unfortunately his sister died a still born. So we filled the part of his sister and his mother. The ferris wheel starts to creek and turn as we get more and more depressed thinking over how our life was. Once we get off the ferris wheel we are led down another hill, where we learn that the park was built on old haunted land. We also learn that people died all the time while this park was being built.Chapter 3After we learn this, we go to the Bumper Cars where we learn that our character was hospitalized and injected and tested on with something. Nothing much else is learned other than we're depressed. during the end of the chapter, a bumper car taes life and starts to drive wildly towards us, unfortunately this game does not come with audio sliders, so the music was so loud compared to the SFX. Nothing was terrifying due to this.Chapter 4We head over to this lake with this weird carnival theme. There's a giant spinning ride in the center of a pier, with extremely loud, over used, carnival music. I just ran around the entier pier neglecting anything scary, looking for clues about the park and my character. Fortunately, this area is saved by the backstory of ""Steve/Chad the Mascot."" This is where we see an Eye-Witness report of a murder that Chad commited. A person waiting in line was watching Chad make an ice sculpture, as he was very good at it. Chad was seen taking his time, but whatever he was carv ing had so much detail people could not look away. The eye witness reports seeing a face popping out of the ice, with no eyes and no teeth. Just as the eye witness was looking at the sculptor, two teens walked over and laughed at Chad. Chad took the ice pick and stabbed the teenagers over and over, until he got an eyeball out and put it in the hole of the ice sculptor.This was a pretty interesting eye-witness report and it got my hopes up that Chad would soon scare the poop outta me.Soon after this report, we walk up a hill to an employees room, where we learn a fellow employee of Chad had died. This employee had a note written saying how Chad never took the suit off, and it stank like decaying flesh. The employee said they hated Chad and sometimes he would walk over and stare at her. As soon as we put the note down, the lights on the inside of the room flash and we can see Chad's siloutte standing over an employee, holding his ice pick.Chapter 5We head over to the carnival section of the map, but this area provides us with little to no information. The only detail here is that a child was killed behind the cotton candy maker. then we go into this weird psychadelic world, which feels like an Oxy trip, where everything is slow motion and the devil's laughter echoes in the background. Nothing more than that... We pic kup a bottle of pills and a roller coaster ticket thoughChapter 6 [/]The roller coaster opens a whole new perspective on our character. During our ride, we are greeted by a mysterious slender-man esq, person who is telling us how horrible we are. As we ride the coaster, we get these insane strobe lights which are supposedly flash backs to the hospital when we were having Callum. This idea was horrible by design and horrible narritavely. It provided little and was only to show that the game would have a roller coaster. We pick up our first and only item, the Flashlight.Chapter 7We head into the house fo horrors where we learn...! WeKILLED CALLUM!We also learn that we are in purgatory, and we have to relive the same day over and over. The same scene over and over. I must have walked through the same area 11 times. Each with slighly changed and more evil aspects. We learn that we are the Ice pick killer, and that Callum was the innocent victim behind the cotton candy tent. Then that's the end of the game. It was an okay expirece.ProsAlright narrativeInteresting lore and back story for the parkAtmopshereConsGameplay was extremely boringLinear story lineNo items are secretsOverallI'd give this game a6/10It was alright, the only redeeming quality is the atmosphere. If you like dark themed areas and spooky theme parks, this is your kind of game"
