76561198087345773,Recommended,402020,35284601,Posted: 28 September,all,sunny29990,"Ok, I have mixed feelings about this game and I love psychological horror games. I have played lots of them. First of all I would like to say that the settings of this game are done quite well. The amusement park is spooky and eerie and reminded me of those classic childhood horror movies of abandoned haunted parks. It felt really good to explore and soak in the atmosphere and enjoy the rides.But apart from that the story is told in a very ambiguous way dropping us with some vague clues on what happened with the main character but clearly not explaining enough to build an assumed explanation. I have played a similar psychedelic horror game like this, ""Layers Of Fear"" and even though it was also ambiguous it clearly dropped enough clues to form some explanations on what happened.  While the story of this game is quite engaging it would have done some more effort to explain on what exactly happened. Add to the fact that I got to know later that it was made  as a spin off and is set in the same universe as another game ""The Secret World"" made it more confusing. I can think of one or two things that may have happened but not enough to get a satisfying conclusion. It could have been so much more as the game definitely had the standards to be a good psychological horror game from the rest of the things it did.The rides in the game offered a little insight into the mindset of the main character and they were unique in itself. Also, the graphics were really beautiful and creepy and the game performance was good. I just wish the story could have been a little more polished so that I could have enjoyed it more. I never complain about the length of a game because if i enjoyed it for the time i played it then its good enough for me. You can buy this game on a sale and play it to experience the game settings and atmosphere of the amusement park. Other than that, I am hopeful the developers will make a more engaging story driven title in the future for us horror fans."
