76561198011917951,Recommended,402020,18991263,"Posted: 10 November, 2015",all,anorsworthy,"The Park is a fascinating experience.  You start the game at the entrance of an amusement park, with your child having left behind his teddy bear in the park. When you go to the help desk, your child runs in and you must follow his trail through the park.I'm actually fine with the concept of an ""interactive movie"", and I'm particularly open to ones in the horror genre. The Park was more memorable than I had hoped. The early parts can be a bit slow, but the game steadily picks up as you get further along. The game doesn't rely on the creepiness of the park alone. A lot of the game is focused on exploring the psychological state of the mother, and watching her mind unravel the deeper she goes into the park.While I was satisfied with the overall experience, I do feel that the developers  could've done more in certain areas.  The areas of the park seem bigger than they need to be. Not that I explored every nook and cranny, but I did try to look around, and it seems like there's not usually a reward for going off the beaten path. One of the things I value most in horror games aren't the monsters or the jumpscares, but finding creepy little oddities scattered around the environment. Although ""following the trail"" is an important theme in the game, I think there could've been a bit more detail for the players who like to explore. Like many horror games, there's a large focus on reading notes. But in many cases, the letters are way too small, and I had to practically press my face against my screen to be able to make out what they said.The game really has two stories, the history and nature of the park, and exploring the character of the mother. By the end, I felt like one was resolved, and the other wasn't. I've never played The Secret World and I don't know anything about it, and perhaps playing that game would clear up the remaining questions I have, but a spin-off should be able to stand on its own. It seems that a large part of the story is symbolic, but I feel that may have resulted in a somewhat weak ending.I did have noticeable frame rate issues, but my PC is fairly old by now, and I don't have the technical know-how to say if it's my computer or the game. The indoor areas usually ran fine though.If you aren't put off by a lack of real gameplay and just want to immerse yourself in the story and the environment, then I would definitely recommend playing through The Park."
