76561198043584925,Not Recommended,402020,22545782,"Posted: 21 April, 2016",all,danmill2k5,"Hmmm...Ok. It's a good concept. It's different, unusual, out there.I played 56 minutes in total before requesting a refund.But that's all it is. A good ""concept"". I requested a refund for this game because of the reasons below.The way the story is written is very unrealistic. Let me explain below:The start of the game finds you as Callum's mother, in the car park of the theme park, and he has left his teddybear in the park. The park has closed and the gates are locked, so you go to check at the ticket office to see if it's been handed in to lost property.Fine. No issues there.Next, the member of staff you are talking to says that Callum has just gone back inside the park. The gates are locked, and you can't get in, so how the hell can he? The ticket office man says he will unlock the gates and allow you back in to go and get him.How can Callum get inside the park if the gates are locked? That's the first major flaw.He could have been kidnapped by ""something"", or ventured through a hole in the fence, but he goes through the locked gates.I tried to overlook that, and carried on playing. Next, you have to go up some escalators.As you ascend, everything goes dark and the game ""fades out"". Suddenly you are back, and it's dark, and the park is in disarray. Broken lights, overgrown, untidy etc.There's no explanation why this happens, and the character you're playing doesn't react to it, it's as if it's a normal event and supposed to happen. It doesn't make a lot of sense.Another point is that you can ride all of the rides in the park, and this is part of the game (you have to ride them to hear more of the story).Why would you venture into a theme park looking for your child, to start riding the rides? What makes it worse is that the rides are supposidly ""dangerous"", yet you still ride them. Why are you doing this when you're supposed to be looking for Callum?The game is a little distrubing in places too. The mother, although she is in the park looking for Callum, starts calling him ""little f***"""" and saying she says she should just leave him there. Why would you do that if you've gone into the park in the first place?When anything scary happens to make you jump, you get a Steam Achievement. This pops up on the right hand side in a box, ruining the effect and distracting you away from what has just happened.And the ""acheievements"" aren't an achievement at all. They're things you have to do in the game to contiunue, but you still get rewarded for. I played for approx 56 minutes and unlocked 64% of them already!Walking around the park, you find accident reports. Why would these just be left on top of a bumpercar or on the outside wall of the ferris wheel control box?This is a story game. Far too much story and spoken audio, and not nearly enough game play. It just gets boring and repetitive.The controls on this game didn't work properly for me. I'm using a keyboard and mouse, but when holding shift to run, it only did it half of the time.This will eat away at your graphics card too! I can easily run Planet Coaster, which can be very graphic hungry, but I had to turn the graphics down to medium on this game, just to make it playable.The lack of realism in this game, such as riding the rides (why?), events that don't make sense, long audio speeches and a story that's unbelieveable, really spoils the game in my opinion.As I've said, it's a great idea, but it could be told and written so much better. Callum could have been kidnapped by someone or something and notes left to tell the mother he is in The Park. That could have been the reason why she had to go in there. Not because Callum ran through locked gates (!) and then she has to find him. Why would he keep ignoring his mothers calls and continue to go further into the park?Maybe I'm missing something. It's a creepy, scary, dark idea, great for a horror/ thriller game, but the realism is severely lacking, making it unbelieveable, unrealistic, and just not half as scary :("
