,Recommended,402020,18847149,"Posted: 2 November, 2015",all,Katosepe,"The Park is an interesting game that's very difficult to nail down. I will give it a recommend because I did enjoy my experience with the game but it comes with the caveat that not everyone will enjoy this game. In fact, I would guess most people will not enjoy this game but for those who can appreciate it, it is an interesting dive into the mind of a mother, torn between societal expectations and her own experiences.The trailers show The Park as being a horror game but in reality, it's closer to a game like Dear Esther or Gone Home than something like The Evil Within or Five Nights at Freddys. This is because, there really isn't any danger in The Park. You cannot die or lose or anything throughout the game. For me, this realization took away most of the tension I was feeling. There are some creepy jump scares, sure, but I was never concerned by what I was seeing as, for most of the game, there was nothing I could do about it anyway.Because of this, players are more likely to enjoy the story rather than any sense of accomplishment for braving the unknown. The storyline is split between two major mysteries. Not to spoil anything, as you venture throughout the titular park, you learn about the history of the park itself and the history of the player character, a mother chasing after her son throughout his favorite amusement park that clearly has seen better days.Wandering around, you ride the various rides in the park which set you up in on-rails scenes which result in something creepy happening or more backstory from the mother. This is really where the game falters a bit. You learn very quickly that backstory will come about by walking to the next ride and riding it. It becomes very formulaic so that you can expect when things will happen. As such, the journey to each ride becomes a bit tedious, further eliminating the atmosphere that the game is trying to generate.This next bit may contain very minor spoilers but really just my reaction to the conclusion without any details. If that's too much spoiler for you, you have been warned:So players will be playing this for the story but the story itself, is hit or miss. Well, really, hit and miss. The mother's story with her son is interesting and comes to a solid, if not predictable, conclusion. The story of the park itself, though, is much more open-ended and not in a good way. You are given bits and pieces of story about the park throughout the game but it never seems to really go anywhere. At least, I didn't find anything in my playthrough that wrapped it up. I found this rather disappointing.Ultimately, if you enjoy games like Dear Esther or Gone Home and would like something in that vein with a bit of a horror vibe to it, The Park will do. It may not be the most memorable or revolutionary entry in the burgeoning genre, but it's worth a playthrough. If that doesn't sound interesting or if you're on a budget and want some bang for your buck, The Park isn't the game for you.My Experience: Before reviewing this game, I completed the game once, missing a couple achievements in the process. I don't plan on going back for them any time soon."
