,Recommended,402020,20350251,"Posted: 6 January, 2016",all,olliepm,"Overall, this game is an absoloute piece of art and has shot right up into my top 5 somewhere.   Do you love Bioshock?  Abstract storytelling?  Rollercoasters?If you're anything like me, you do love Bioshock and will love The Park for the same sort of reasons.  It has that same level of narrative immersion that makes you feel like you are truly a part of the story.  The eeire horror environment is stunning and I would've explored every detail of it if I wasn't afraid something terrible was about to happen to me at all times.  There are even some philisophical vibes to The Park, so it's a must play for Bioshock fans.  As a bonus there are amusment park rides to enjoy.The sound design is actually some of the best audio work I've heard in a game for a long time. In conjunction with the visual and/or narrative events, the sound becomes part of a multisensory expereince; you don't actually notice the sound so much as notice how the whole game is making you feel as part of that multisensory experience.  (You will only expereince this properly if you play in the dark with headphones)I'm certain that Funcom know their psychology.  It is entirely appropriate to call The Park a 'psychological' horror as at times it was noticable that the gameplay was likely designed to affect/manipulate the players mental state.  An example of this might be gameplay that is designed to confuse the player first, and THEN deliver the next part of the story so that it illicits a stronger emotion in the player.There is a lot of realism in the game considering the concept is entirely fictional too.  Something blew my mind in this regard that I won't detail in case I spoil it, but Funcom know exactly what the walls would look like if you had ingested magic mushrooms...  EXACTLY what the walls would look like..."
76561198117055124,Recommended,402020,20435704,"Posted: 9 January, 2016",all,Chezomac,"A couple of jumpscares, and a very disturbing story."
,Recommended,402020,20355525,"Posted: 6 January, 2016",all,Juldans,"A common fear is to fail as parents and lose our children. Another common fear is to lose our minds. What if it is already too late?In The Park you play as Lorraine, a single mother. The game begins at her car on an otherwise empty parking lot outside the Atlantic Island Park, an amusement park that has just closed for the day. Your son, Callum, has lost his teddy bear and you go to the entrance to ask the attendant if it has been found. Suddenly you hear Callum enter the park. You need to search for him in the now empty and dark amusement areas. While doing this you learn more about the history of the park, and also, maybe more importantly, more about yourself through objects you find and through an inner monologue. Have you failed as a mother?The gameplay in The Park is very basic: You walk around in the park, click on some objects and shout for Callum, and there are no real choices you can make in the game. However, The Park is not really a game in the traditional sense. Instead the focus is on the atmosphere, the suspense and the storytelling and I think that these aspects are well executed. Despite some unnecessary, and honestly stupid, jump scares I found the story very scary on a psychological level, and towards the end I was also moved to such degree that I played with tears in my eyes. That does not happen often when I am by the computer. Since I often cry watching films and reading books it seems that my eyes consider The Park to be an expression closer to those formats than that of other games.The Atlantic Island Park is a location in The Secret World, an MMO I have played excessively the last couple of years, and the storyline in The Park fits well into that universe."
